oc get kiali kiali-monitoring -n kiali -o jsonpath='{.spec.deployment.cluster_wide_access}{"\n"}'
oc get kiali kiali-monitoring -n kiali -o jsonpath='{.spec.deployment.accessible_namespaces}{"\n"}'

# 2. Does the operator already own any monitoring-view-style CRB under a different name?
oc get clusterrolebinding -o json \
  | jq -r '.items[] | select(.roleRef.name=="cluster-monitoring-view") | .metadata.name + "  ownerRefs=" + ((.metadata.ownerReferences // []) | tostring)'
```

Interpretation:
- If `cluster_wide_access: true` on the CR **and** the operator manages its own monitoring binding under a different name — then the live `dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view` is a redundant manual leftover, and it's clean to delete + let Helm own it.
- If the operator expects *this exact name*, deleting it will cause the operator to recreate it (unlabeled) within seconds, and your Helm conflict returns immediately. In that case, don't put it in Helm — remove the CRB from the chart and let the operator own it.

Note your chart's `values.yaml` has `kiali.deployment.cluster_wide_access: true`, which strongly suggests the operator does manage cluster-wide RBAC. That's the pattern that makes me want you to confirm #1/#2 before deleting.

## Recommended path (assuming #1/#2 confirm the live CRB is a manual orphan, not operator-reconciled)

Since semantics match, prefer **adopt-in-place** over delete — it eliminates even the brief RBAC gap and achieves the identical end state (Helm ownership):

```bash
oc annotate clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  meta.helm.sh/release-name=epay-common \
  meta.helm.sh/release-namespace=dev-epay-common --overwrite
oc label clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  app.kubernetes.io/managed-by=Helm --overwrite
```

Then run the deploy pipeline. Helm adopts it, upgrade proceeds. If you specifically want the delete-and-recreate route instead, it's also fine given the semantics match — sequence below.

## Delete-and-recreate sequence (if you prefer a clean recreate)

```bash
# backup already exists: /tmp/crb-live-full.yaml  ✅
oc delete clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view
# immediately watch it does NOT get recreated by the operator before your pipeline runs:
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -w   # Ctrl-C after ~15s if absent
# run the deploy job, then verify Helm ownership:
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  -o jsonpath='managed-by={.metadata.labels.app\.kubernetes\.io/managed-by}{" release="}{.metadata.annotations.meta\.helm\.sh/release-name}{"\n"}'
```

**Impact during the gap:** Kiali's ServiceAccount loses `cluster-monitoring-view` for the seconds between delete and recreate. Effect is limited to Kiali's metrics/graph panels temporarily returning no Prometheus data. The Kiali pod keeps running; no payment/transaction service is affected — this binding is purely mesh-observability. RBAC restores instantly on recreate, no restart needed.

## Rollback plan

You already captured the full object, so rollback is a one-liner. Keep `/tmp/crb-live-full.yaml`; also stage a clean re-appliable copy:

```bash
# Clean apply-ready backup (strip server fields), do this NOW before any change
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o yaml \
  | grep -vE '^\s*(uid|resourceVersion|creationTimestamp|generation):' \
  > /tmp/crb-rollback.yaml
```

Rollback scenarios:

1. **Pipeline fails / Kiali panels lose data after the change** — recreate the exact original binding:
   ```bash
   oc apply -f /tmp/crb-rollback.yaml
   oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o jsonpath='{.roleRef.name}{"\n"}'
   ```

2. **If you used adopt-in-place and want to undo the ownership stamp** (revert to orphan state):
   ```bash
   oc annotate clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
     meta.helm.sh/release-name- meta.helm.sh/release-namespace-
   oc label clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
     app.kubernetes.io/managed-by-
   ```

3. **Full Helm release rollback** (if the upgrade partially applied then failed):
   ```bash
   helm history epay-common -n dev-epay-common
   helm rollback epay-common <LAST_GOOD_REVISION> -n dev-epay-common
   ```

Verification after any rollback — confirm Kiali can read monitoring again:
